  "prompt": "Who invented Classical music?",
  "response": "Classical music, as we understand it today, is not the invention of a single person but rather the result of centuries of musical development across Europe. The term \"Classical music\" generally refers to the formal musical tradition of the Western world, encompassing a wide range of styles and periods from the medieval era to the present day.\n\nHowever, the **Classical period** in music history (roughly 1750\u20131820) is often associated with composers like **Franz Joseph Haydn**, **Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart**, and **Ludwig van Beethoven**. These composers helped define the characteristics of the Classical style, which emphasized clarity, balance, and structural elegance.\n\nThe roots of Classical music can be traced back to earlier periods, such as the **Medieval** (500\u20131400), **Renaissance** (1400\u20131600), and **Baroque** (1600\u20131750) eras, where composers like **Johann Sebastian Bach** and **George Frideric Handel** laid the groundwork for later developments.\n\nSo, while there isn\u2019t a single inventor of Classical music, it evolved through the contributions of countless composers, performers, and theorists over centuries.",
